book/first-steps/making-decisions.html.body:
Making Decisions
Up to this point you should be able to write a program that has some variables and can do some math. That is a great starting point, but honestly it's probably not all that interesting yet. As humans, we make many decisions every day, and while not always rational they're most likely founded on some amount of information. Almost all programs make decisions too; however, they are founded entirely on fact. And given the same information, the exact same decision will be made every single time (sadly the same cannot be said for us humans).
What If...
Every decision that a computer makes is based on what is called a statement and whether that statement is true, or whether it is false. Everything that is a value in JS can also be considered a true or a false value. Later in this section I've listed out all the types of values and their truthiness. The most common way for a program to make a decision is to use the if statement:
if () {
    // Then...

}

The structure of an if statement introduces the use of an opening ( { ) and closing ( } ) curly bracket. For the sake of not giving you misinformation, these are not required when used under certain conditions (which we wont get into right now). However, for the purposes of simplicity, think of them as something you must always have when writing an if statement. That way the main structure of your if statement will always be the same. What the curly braces do is allow you to tell JS that the section of code inside them () is only to be executed when the  is true. I don't have a good metaphor for if statements other than they seem to line up with how we as humans can perform actions based on objectively making a decision. For example:

if the baby is crying, then try to comfort the baby.
if the house is on fire, then get out of the freaking house.
if the car won't start, then check whether it has any gas.

I'll write these examples out in a moment. But first, here is some code where we are just using the the literal boolean value to show what happens when the statement is true or false:
Something that evaluates to true
if (true) {
    // The code inside the brackets will execute
}

// More code, always executed

Something that evaluates to false
if (false) {
    // The code inside the brackets will NOT execute
}

// More code, always executed

Other examples:
var theBabyIsCrying = true;
if (theBabyIsCrying) {
    // Do something to comfort the baby
}

var theHouseIsOnFire = true;
if (theHouseIsOnFire) {
    // Get out of the freaking house
}

Now is probably a good time to introduce the not operator which is just an exclamation point !. This just takes the opposite of what ever it is next to. So a true value becomes false and a false value becomes true. The not operator always directly precedes whatever it is you want to take the opposite of. So, using the above examples:
var theBabyIsCrying = false;
if (!theBabyIsCrying) {
    // This is good, you are not distracted by the baby
    // Go about your business
}

var theHouseIsOnFire = false;
if (!theHouseIsOnFire) {
    // This is pretty normal
    // Not a whole lot to do here
}

To illustrate the car starting example we need to introduce the else statement. The code contained in the brackets of the else statement will get executed if the if statement evaluates to false.
if () {
    // Then...

} else {
    // Else

}

var theCarStarts = false;
if (theCarStarts) {
    // Yay! you can drive wherever it is you wanted to go
} else {
    // Check to see if it has any gas
}

var theCarStarts = true;
if (!theCarStarts) {
    // Check to see if it has any gas
} else {
    // Yay! you can drive wherever it is you wanted to go
}

The above is the if else statement. From here on I will refer to any combination of if, else, and else if (which you'll see next) generically as an "if statement".
The last thing to add is the else if statement. Let me preface talking about this by giving you some rules for if statements that are pretty simple:
1) There must be one, and only one, "if" in an if statement
2) There can optionally be a single "else" at the end of in an if statement
3) There can be zero or more "else if" statements preceding an "if" statement in an if statement
The else if statement lets you add additional things to check should the original if statement evaluate to false. Since you can have multiple else ifs, think of them as being checked in the order in which you have them listed, whichever one evaluates to true first (if any of them) will get its code between its brackets executed.
I'll give a few examples to hopefully make this more clear:
if (true) {
    // Executes
}

if (true) {
    // Executed
} else {
    // Not executed
}

if (false) {
    // Not executed
} else if (true) {
    // Executed
}

if (false) {
    // Not executed
} else if (false) {
    // Not executed
} else {
    // Executed
}

if (false) {
    // Not executed
} else if (false) {
    // Not executed
} else if (false) {
    // Not executed
} else if (true) {
    // Executed
} else {
    // Not executed
}

Nesting
The last thing I want to give you is the ability to do what is called nesting. This generally refers to putting code that uses brackets (like if statements) inside some other code that uses brackets (again, like if statements). It's much easier shown than explained with words:
if (true) {
    // The following code is executed
    if (false) {
        // Not executed
    } else {
        // Executed
        // We cold keep going with the nesting if we wanted to have more conditions
    }
} else {
    // Not executed
}

var theHouseIsOnFire = true
var theDoorsAreLocked = false
if (theHouseIsOnFire) { // This is true
    // Oh no, we'd better get out
    if (theDoorsAreLocked) { // This is false
        // If this were true, hopefully we could unlock the doors
    } else {
        // Phew, we're able to easily get out of the house
    }
} else {
    // This is just a normal day
}

But Wait, There's More
This should get you going for now. More advanced and concise decision making will be covered in the intermediate topic. If the idea of not knowing the best way of doing something from the start concerns you, then I can offer this piece of advice:
One of the best parts about programming is that if you have done something one way, and then learn a better way to do it, there is nothing stopping you from changing it.
Depending on what you've done, it may be more or less complicated to change it in the future, but that in and of it self is also part of the leaning process. Over time you will get better at writing code than can be updated, rewritten, and maintained.

book/intermediate-topics/objects.html.body:
For the first part of this section we will use the term "box" in place of a structure that is called a "JavaScript object".
Imagine you have a box. But this is a special box. You can put whatever you want inside this box, and It can be instantly resized to whatever size you need it to be.
This is a box (it's empty):
{}

You can assign your box to a variable:
var box = {};

Remember how this box can instantly be resized to any size you need? Let's see that in action. The best part is that you don't have to do anything other than put things in the box. And label them of course... you don't want to forget what's in the box. Feel free to literally imagine labels on the things you put in the box. Here is the basic structure of a box:
{
    'label': 1234,
}

Boxes are great for structuring and organizing information, and can contain pretty much whatever you want:
A string:
{
    'aString': 'Hi! I'm a string!',
}

Some numbers:
{
    'anInteger': 42,
    'aFloat': 3.14,
}

A boolean:
{
    aBoolean: true
}

Other boxes:
{
    'anEmptyBox': {},
    'aBoxWithStuff': {
        'aString': 'Hi! I'm a string!',
    'anInteger': 42,
    'aFloat': 3.14,
    },
}

An array:
{
    'anArray': [1, 2, 3, 4, 5],
}

Even functions:
{
    'add': function(a, b) {
        return a + b
    },
}

Here is a practical example of a what you might organize in a box (using a toy box as the example):
var toyBox = {
    'lego': {
        '2x2': 50,
        '2x4': 75,
        '1x2': 30,
        '1x4': 40,
    },
    'dolls': {
        'ken': {
            'hair': 'brown',
            'eyes': 'blue',
        },
        'barbie': {
            'hair': 'blonde',
            'eyes': 'brown',
        },
        'elmo': {
            'hair': 'red',
            'eyes': 'black',
        },
        'giJoe': {
            'hair': 'black',
            'eyes': 'black',
        }
    },
    'vehicles': [
        'Race Car',
        'Truck',
        'Plane',
        'Helicopter',
    ]
}

At this point we will start referring to "boxes" by their correct term, "objects". And "labels" and "things" will be referred to as "properties" and "values". Also, properties do not require quotes around them (unless you want to have a property that is a JavaScript keyword, or starts with a number, or contains an operator), so they won't be used unless necessary.
Objects are very flexible, but have a very basic structure as covered above. Something worth playing with is how you like to visually structure your objects. The format used above is pretty common, but there's nothing stopping you from putting it all on one line (word wrap prevents it from all being on a single line here, but try copying it into your code editor):
{'anEmptyBox': {}, 'aBoxWithStuff': {'aString': 'Hi! I\'m a string!','anInteger': 42, 'aFloat': 3.14}}

Now that you have some objects to work with the next question is probably, "How do I get stuff out of a box/object?". It's actually very simple, let's use an example from above. But before jumping into that it is worth mentioning that there are two ways to access the value of a property. Either using dot notation or array "index" notation. Array notation can be used to access any property, while dot notation cannot (specifically properties that start with numbers and/or contain operators).
var myObject = {
    anInteger: 42,
    aFloat: 3.14,
}

To get a value from it (using dot notation):
var x = myObject.anInteger;

"x" would now have the value of 42.
And for a more complex example using the toyBox from above (referencing inner objects):
var x = toyBox.dolls.ken.hair; // Dot notation
var x = toyBox['dolls']['ken']['hair']; // Array index notation

"x" is now "brown"
And for using both dot notation and array index notation:
var x = toyBox.lego['2x4'];

"x" is now 75.
Array index notation is required for '2x4' here because it starts with a number. The following is NOT VALID syntax:
var x = toyBox.lego.2x4; // This will fail to execute

It is also possible to access an object's property using a variable and array index notation:
var a ='2x4';
var x = toyBox.lego[a];

"x" is again 75
The following is valid syntax, but will not give you the value that toyBox.lego[a] will:
var a ='2x4';
var x = toyBox.lego.a; // "a" is not a known property of toyBox.lego

Now that you've seen how to access a value in an object, the next step is to add a property to an object or update a property on an object. This is done simply by placing the object access on the left hand side of the equals operator.
To update a property:
toyBox.lego['1x2'] = 50;

To add a property:
toyBox.lego['1x6'] = 10;


Use this object to answer the following questions:
var car = {
    wheels: 4,
    color: 'red',
    topSpeed: 88.8,
    Features: {
        airBags: 6,
        bluetooth: false,
        powerWindows: true,
        '4x4': true,
    }
}

How would you access the color of the car using dot notation?
How would you access the color of the car using array index notation?
Change the color of the car.
How would you access the '4x4' feature of the car (to figure out whether it has that feature or not)?
Increase the topSpeed of the car by 10.
Add 2 extra air bags to the car.
Add the bluetooth feature to the car by 10.
Add your own feature to the car!
Bonus:
How would you access and "console.log" each of the features (assume you don't know what the features are)? Hint: use a "for loop".

book/intermediate-topics/functions.html.body:
Functions
Up until now if you have been playing with JS on your own you have probably found that you were repeating yourself a lot. Maybe checking the same conditions in an if statement in multiple places throughout your code, or logging the same string with multiple variables in more than one place. This is a (non-medical) condition called is called code duplication, and the best cure for it is functions.
Functions allow you to break your code up into logical, reusable sections. You also get to give these sections names. When naming a function, it should be something that describes what it does and is hopefully easy to remember.
Function Syntax
Structurally, functions look a little like a single if statement, but have a little more to them and are much more powerful. Let's get some terms out of the way. When you write a function, that is called "defining" a function. And when you want to use a function and have it do something, that is called "calling" a function.
// Defining a function
function sayHello() {
    console.log('Hello!')
}

// Calling the function
sayHello()

If you run this example, you'll see that it simply outputs "Hello!". You might be thinking "well this seems excessive, all it is doing is logging out a string", and you would be right, it is excessive (unless of course you want to be super friendly and say hello a bunch of times, then it might seem a little more practical). However, the point here is to demonstrate the bare minimum to create a function an have it produce a tangible result. The key here is to realize that you can put anything you want inside a function and then call that function as many times as you would like. This enables you to write some code once and use it as many times as you want, by simply calling your function. Before moving on and making things more interesting, let me give you another metaphor.
Try to think of a task you do regularly in your every day life. Give it a name, and think of the inputs it requires. These would be materials, tools, or information required to perform your task. Bonus points if it has some sort of result or product... an output. Also think about the steps involved in your task. Keep this task in mind, along with it's inputs, steps, and outputs, as we go through the next few examples.
Now let's make the above function a little more interesting:
// Defining a function with a single parameter: whatToSay
function saySomething(whatToSay) {
    console.log(whatToSay)
}

// Calling the function with a parameter value of 'Hello!'
saySomething('Hello!')

// Calling the function with a parameter value of 'How are you!'
saySomething('How are you?')

// Calling the function with a parameter that is a variable
var jackSays = 'I can jump!';
saySomething(jackSays);

Now we have added what is called a function parameter; this would be one of the inputs to the task I had you think through. Parameters allow you to create variables that are special to the execution of your function, and you can have as many as you would like. If your function has parameters, you need to give those parameters values when you call your function. In the case of the above example, the function seems to expect a string for the first parameter. I say seems because we can pass whatever value(s) we want into any function
Here is a slightly more practical function (that seems to accept numbers):
function add(numberA, numberB) {
    return numberA + numberB
}

var result1 = add(2, 3)
var result2 = add(10, 10)

console.log(result1)
console.log(result2)

Now we have two parameters and a return value. The return value is the output to your function, which you are free to do whatever you wish with, like assign it to a variable. The return value is completely optional, and if you do not specify one then it defaults to a value of "undefined".
That is essentially all there is to functions. A bit (or sometimes a lot) of code that you can reuse wherever you please. It accepts any number of inputs that you choose and and has an optional output. Here are a few more examples:
// A function to average an array
function averageArray(array) {
    var total = 0;

    // Total all the items in the array
    for (var i in array) {
        total = total + array[i];
    }

    // Divide the total by the number of items
    return total / array.length;
}

// Creating an array
var myArray = [2, 5, 6, 9, 17]

// There's no need to assign it to a variable
// if all that is needed it to output the result
console.log(average(myArray))

Oh, and one last thing. Remember how everything is a value? Yep, you can assign functions to variables to:
// Defining what is called an anonymous function
// and assigning it to a variable 
var myFunction = function() {
    // It does a thing...
}

myFunction();

And pass functions into other functions:
var ifEven = function(number) {
    console.log(number + ' is even')
}

var ifOdd = function(number) {
    console.log(number + ' is odd')
}

var checkEvenOdd = function(number, callIfEven, callIfOdd) {
    if (number % 2 === 0) {
        callIfEven(number)
    } else {
        callIfOdd(number)
    }
}

checkEvenOdd(5, ifEven, ifOdd)
checkEvenOdd(42, ifEven, ifOdd)
checkEvenOdd(1987, ifEven, ifOdd)

This is definitely a contrived example, but it is meant to demonstrate the flexibility of JS.
Functions in Functions
In JS you can nest functions within functions (...within functions, ad infinitum). This will be important when learning about scope.

function logThings() {
    function simpleLog(string) {
        console.log(string);
    }

    simpleLog('This')
    simpleLog('Is')
    simpleLog('How')
    simpleLog('Functions')
    simpleLog('Within')
    simpleLog('Functions')
    simpleLog('Work!')
}

logThings()

// This will intentionally fail, to demonstrate that the inner 
// function is not available outside it's container function
simpleLog()

One last point to make about everything being a value. You can return functions from other functions, which will make more sense once you understand scope better. Here we are calling a function to create and return another "customized" function. You can then use this function anywhere you have access to the variable to which it is assigned.

function createAnAdder(number1, number2) {
    // This returns a function that will return the added
    // values of the numbers that are passed in
    // If this is too confusing, the scope section should
    // help clear it up
    return function() {
        return number1 + number2
    }
}

// Assign a function to "myAdder" that adds 3 and 4 any time you call it
var myAdder = createAnAdder(3, 4);

console.log(myAdder());
console.log(myAdder());
console.log(myAdder());

book/intermediate-topics/scope.html.body:
Scope
If you feel like you have a grasp on functions, then the next topic to tackle is scope. Scope is a difficult concept to explain with words, so it is probably most easily demonstrated by a few examples:

// This variable is global and in the global scope
var aGlobal = 42

// Functions create a new scope when they runs
function myFunction() {
    // This variable only exists inside this function
    var aLocal = 'I am local to this function'

    // This variable has the same name, but it's value
    // only exists inside this function because we're
    // using "var"
    // It does not overwrite the value of "aGlobal" that is declared above
    var aGlobal = 'I am also local to this function'

    console.log(aLocal)
    console.log(aGlobal)
}

// This function also creates it's own scope when it runs
function modifyAGlobal() {
    // We can modify the global variable by not declaring
    // a new "var"
    aGlobal = 777
}

myFunction()

// Notice how aGlobal is still 42 here
console.log(aGlobal)

modifyAGlobal()

// Now notice how aGlobal has been modified
console.log(aGlobal)

The above code demonstrates how each function creates it's own scope, and has access to the scope "above it". Scope is relative to the place where the function is defined. This means it doesn't matter where you call a function from, as it will always have access to the scopes above it.
Here is another example to show this a little differently, with one function calling another.
// These variables are in the global scope
var varA = 1
var varB = 2

// These three functions are in the global scope
function functionA() {
    var varC = 'C'
}

function functionB() {
    var varD = 'D'
}

function functionC() {
    var varE = 'E'

    functionA()
}

Functions A, B, and C are defined within the global scope, so they are tied to that scope.
1) If we call functionA, then it has access to the variables varA, varB, and, in it's own scope varC.
2) If we call functionC, then it has access to the variables varA, varB, and varE. You can also see that it will call functionA... but functionA behaves the same as in #1. It does not have access to anything within functionC, just varA, varB, and varC.
Functions have no knowledge about the variables in other functions. Unless you define a function within another function (which we did earlier in the "functions" section):

// This function takes an array and adds up all the values,
// multiplying each value by the length of the array
// I don't know why you would want to do this, but it demonstrates the point
function weirdMath(theArray) {
    var total = 0;

    // This function only exists within the scope of weirdMath
    function addValueTimesLength(value) {
        total = total + value * theArray.length
    }

    for (var i in theArray) {
        addValueTimesLength(theArray[i])
    }

    return total
}

var myArray = [1, 2, 3, 5, 8, 13]
console.log(weirdMath(myArray))
